node.title: Photographs capture extent of floods in north-west NSW
node.description: These images show the impact of floodwaters inundating the saturated plains of the NSW north-west, cutting off towns and submerging crops.
node.content:
["Downpours that swept across the NSW north-west this week in falls measuring in the hundreds of millimetres have sent floodwaters across the saturated plains, cutting off towns and submerging crops.\u00a0", "The Namoi River at Gunnedah has swollen to 7.84\u00a0metres, spilling through backyards and damaging businesses.", "Locals paddled through floodwaters in canoes to get groceries, while the SES delivered milk and bread to others stuck indoors.", "", "
Gunnedah has received almsot 150mm of rain in the past week.\u00a0(Amy Burling)
", "", "
The Bureau of Meteorology has predicted major flooding in the town is likely on the weekend.(Amy Burling)
", "", "
Locals have called the flood one of the worst in recent years.(Amy Burling)
", "Farmers are frustrated at the downgrading of prize crops, with wheat\u00a0and cotton beneath floodwaters.", "But, despite the devastation, most are philosophical and looking to the bright side \u2014\u00a0the ground will soak up the water, the dams are spilling, and they live on flood plains. What's not to expect?", "", "
The Namoi peaked at Gunnedah at 8.25 metres early on Wednesday, but the BoM says renewed rises are likely.(Amy Burling)
", "", "
The Kamilaroi Highway between Gunnedah and Boggabri has been flooded by the Namoi.(Amy Burling)
", "", "
The SES have conducted multiple rescues from cars stuck in floodwater.(Amy Burling)
", "
Boggabri
", "The Namoi flows downstream to smaller Boggabri, and has flooded the main artery into town, the Kamilaroi Highway.", "The river was today at 8.31\u00a0metres and adjoining Coxs Creek steady at 8.24 metres, but the Bureau of Meteorology was expecting\u00a0those levels to rise\u00a0over the weekend.", "", "
A submerged car on the closed Grain Valley Road southwest of Boggabri.(Andrew Prince)
", "", "
The Bureau of Meteorology says its expecting further rises along the Namoi and Coxs Creek as water flows downstream from Gunnedah.(Andrew Prince)
", "", "
A local SES crew perched on the edge of floodwaters in Boggabri.(Andrew Prince)
", "", "
Mine roads submerged in floodwater just north of Boggabri.(Andrew Prince)
", "", "
The Namoi peaked at Boggabri at 7.98 metres on Thursday morning.(Andrew Prince)
", "", "
Coxs Creek adjoins the Namoi at Boggabri, and continues to rise.\u00a0(Andrew Prince)
", "
Wee Waa
", "The Namoi then flows north-west through Narrabri and out to Wee Waa. The small cotton town is ringed by a levee, protecting the area from rising waters.", "On Thursday, residents flocked to the town's only supermarket to stock up on pasta and canned food. But now, locals say it's pretty quiet.\u00a0They're used to water coming and going.", "The busiest time of day is morning and evening when everyone drives to check the flood levels, which have now reached 7.30\u00a0metres.", "The town is now encircled by water\u00a0and\u00a0the Bureau of Meteorology predicts it\u00a0will stay above the major flood level for the next week.", "", "
Wee Waa is protected by a levee which rings the town.(John Burgess)
", "", "
The Namoi pooling across plains outside the levee bank at Wee Waa.(Ben Schwager)
", "", "
Wee Waa's Chamber of Commerce President, John Tully, at the flooded golf course.(John Burgess)
", "", "
Floodwaters have cut off the main roads out of town.(Ben Schwager)
", "", "
An inundated flood sign along the Pilliga Road, heading west from Wee Waa.(John Burgess)
"]
